webpackJsonp([97786326051841],{350:function(e,a){e.exports={data:{projects:{edges:[{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/mirror/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>I created a smart mirror for my apartment. This display hangs in my apartment and displays information useful at a glance--current time and date, the day\'s weather forecast, personal calendar events, nearby subway times, Citibike dock availability, and daily scheduled reminders.</p>\n<h4>V1 (2016)</h4>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-8576a.jpg"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/jpeg;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Mirror V1"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-893a4.jpg"\n        srcset="/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-25965.jpg 1200w,\n/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-e54c8.jpg 1600w,\n/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-7c0ed.jpg 2400w,\n/static/mirror-v1-a7284f89a91310f08b139a96f5ae28c1-8576a.jpg 3024w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>I created the first non-interactive prototype using an old Dell netbook, plastic two-way mirror, and a custom-made wooden frame.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-8576a.jpg"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 133.33333333333331%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/jpeg;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Mirror V1 Inside"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-893a4.jpg"\n        srcset="/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-25965.jpg 1200w,\n/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-e54c8.jpg 1600w,\n/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-7c0ed.jpg 2400w,\n/static/mirror-v1-inside-0eaa8cef006b753e1620c0bd72638f9c-8576a.jpg 3024w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>The software ran a Node.js server on the backend and a React.js front-end. Glancing at it while getting ready quickly became a part of my morning routine.</p>\n<h4>V2 (2018)</h4>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-8576a.jpg"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 133.33333333333331%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/jpeg;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Mirror V2"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-893a4.jpg"\n        srcset="/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-bbf57.jpg 200w,\n/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-260b8.jpg 400w,\n/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-893a4.jpg 800w,\n/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-25965.jpg 1200w,\n/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-e54c8.jpg 1600w,\n/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-7c0ed.jpg 2400w,\n/static/mirror-v2-435b0261a3d3d90045f727b2253d5cb6-8576a.jpg 3024w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>The newest version is interactive via voice recognition (albeit a very crude version of it, currently). It is an Electron app running on Raspberry Pi that also utilizes React.js for the UI and has a much larger 1080p display.</p>',fields:{slug:"/projects/mirror/"},frontmatter:{title:"Mirror",created:"2018",path:null,description:"My mirror is smarter than yours."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/atlas/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>I led development of <a href="http://atlas.qz.com">Atlas</a>, Quartz\'s <a href="http://qz.com/434425/atlas-the-new-home-for-charts-and-data/">platform for discovering and sharing charts</a>.</p>\n<p>The site is built with React and Node.js and is <a href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2015/04/21/react-to-the-future-with-isomorphic-apps">isomorphic</a>. Quite the buzzword, but it means that the same React javascript components are rendered on the server-side as well as the client-side, which proved to be a huge convenience in terms of development. In the past, I\'ve worked on projects that either forego server-side rendering of content completely (and rely solely on the API) and others that use two separate templates to render the same exact markup (PHP and underscore.js, for example). I introduced the team to Node.js and React + Flux while developing the site.</p>',fields:{slug:"/projects/atlas/"},frontmatter:{title:"Atlas",created:"2015",path:null,description:"A platform for discovering and sharing charts."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/mta-gtfs.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>I needed real-time subway data for a project I was working on so I created a Node.js library to access the real-time MTA subway train schedule API.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/mta-gtfs"><img src="https://img.shields.io/npm/v/mta-gtfs.svg?style=flat-square" alt="npm"></a></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/mta-gtfs"><img src="https://img.shields.io/npm/dt/mta-gtfs.svg?style=flat-square" alt="npm"></a></p>\n<p>It powers a subway widget in the current version of <a href="/projects/mirror">Mirror</a> and has been downloaded ~2k times via npm.</p>',fields:{slug:"/projects/mta-gtfs/"},frontmatter:{title:"MTA GTFS npm package",created:"2015",path:null,description:"A Node.js NYC MTA API library."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/weather-cloud/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>WeatherCloud is an internet-powered hanging lamp that brings the weather inside your home. Inspired by an Etsy cloud lamp and the original prototype of <a href="http://www.richardclarkson.com/cloud/">The Cloud</a> by Richard Clarkson (originally spied at SVA\'s Products of Design lab), I decided to design my own lamp that utilized live weather data to inform its owner of the current weather in their neighborhood. It currently lives happily in my apartment.</p>\n<p>Its electronic guts are comprised of a <a href="https://store.particle.io/?product=particle-photon">Particle Photon</a> (like an Arduino) and a string of LEDs. It uses <a href="https://developer.forecast.io/">Dark Sky Forecast API</a> for its live data.</p>\n<p>There are different light patterns to match each weather pattern. Here are a couple of examples:</p>\n<p>When it\'s a clear day, the cloud glows a warm red-orange...</p>\n<blockquote class="instagram-media" data-instgrm-version="4" style=" background:#FFF; border:0; border-radius:3px; box-shadow:0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width:658px; padding:0; width:99.375%; width:-webkit-calc(100% - 2px); width:calc(100% - 2px);"><div style="padding:8px;"> <div style=" background:#F8F8F8; line-height:0; margin-top:40px; padding:50% 0; text-align:center; width:100%;"> <div style=" background:url(data:image/png;base64,); display:block; height:44px; margin:0 auto -44px; position:relative; top:-22px; width:44px;"></div></div><p style=" color:#c9c8cd; font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; line-height:17px; margin-bottom:0; margin-top:8px; overflow:hidden; padding:8px 0 7px; text-align:center; text-overflow:ellipsis; white-space:nowrap;"><a href="https://instagram.com/p/t7pqqhM1aE/" style=" color:#c9c8cd; font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:17px; text-decoration:none;" target="_top">A video posted by aamaliaa (@aamaliaa)</a> on <time style=" font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; line-height:17px;" datetime="2014-10-09T12:39:02+00:00">Oct 9, 2014 at 5:39am PDT</time></p></div></blockquote>\n<p>and when it\'s raining, naturally, lightning flashes fill the cloud...</p>\n<blockquote class="instagram-media" data-instgrm-version="4" style=" background:#FFF; border:0; border-radius:3px; box-shadow:0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width:658px; padding:0; width:99.375%; width:-webkit-calc(100% - 2px); width:calc(100% - 2px);"><div style="padding:8px;"> <div style=" background:#F8F8F8; line-height:0; margin-top:40px; padding:50% 0; text-align:center; width:100%;"> <div style=" background:url(data:image/png;base64,); display:block; height:44px; margin:0 auto -44px; position:relative; top:-22px; width:44px;"></div></div><p style=" color:#c9c8cd; font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; line-height:17px; margin-bottom:0; margin-top:8px; overflow:hidden; padding:8px 0 7px; text-align:center; text-overflow:ellipsis; white-space:nowrap;"><a href="https://instagram.com/p/3NOCSBM1T7/" style=" color:#c9c8cd; font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:17px; text-decoration:none;" target="_top">A video posted by aamaliaa (@aamaliaa)</a> on <time style=" font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; line-height:17px;" datetime="2015-05-28T01:06:28+00:00">May 27, 2015 at 6:06pm PDT</time></p></div></blockquote>\n<script async defer src="//platform.instagram.com/en_US/embeds.js"></script>',fields:{slug:"/projects/weather-cloud/"},frontmatter:{title:"WeatherCloud",created:"2014",path:null,description:"An internet-connected lamp that shows the weather."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/quartz/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>I joined the team at Quartz right as they were planning a major site redesign and contributed to the development of Quartz 3.0. The <a href="http://qz.com/246831/quartz-has-a-new-look-and-for-the-first-time-a-homepage/">project</a> was a complete overhaul of the original UI with a focus on touchscreen and mobile devices and introduced a homepage for the first time. Quartz is built on Wordpress with Backbone.js on the front-end.</p>',fields:{slug:"/projects/quartz/"},frontmatter:{title:"Quartz 3.0",created:"2014",path:null,description:"A major redesign of qz.com."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/citibike/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>When Citibike was announced, I think I was more excited about the data that would be generated and shared publicly than the bikes themselves. This project was a quick experiment built on top of the real-time Citibike stations data.</p>\n<p>I used Google Maps and d3.js to plot out each of the stations on the map:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="color: green;">green</span> stations have > 5 bikes available</li>\n<li><span style="color: orange;">orange</span> stations have between 1 and 5 bikes available</li>\n<li><span style="color: red;">red</span> stations have 0 bikes available</li>\n<li>a <span style="color: green;">green</span> station with a larger circle radius has more available bikes</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To use the tool, simply enter an origin address and a destination address (both NYC addresses), and hit the "plot" button. Bicycle directions between the closest stations to each of the two points that you\'ve specified will be plotted on the map.</p>',fields:{slug:"/projects/citibike/"},frontmatter:{title:"Citibike",created:"2013",path:null,description:"An exploration with the NYC Citibike API."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/bathroom-vacancy-light/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>I used to live in a 3-bedroom apartment with only one bathroom and wanted an easy way to know when the bathroom was unoccupied without leaving my room (and my bed, for that matter). So, like any other normal person, I decided the solution was to design my own airplane-style lavatory vacancy light for my room.</p>\n<p>I used an Arduino equipped with a magnetic reed switch and a WiFly attached to my bathroom doorframe that transmitted signals using Pusher via wifi. On the receiving end in my bedroom was a Raspberry Pi which was subscribed to the Arduino\'s Pusher channel. When signal was received upon door open and close, the Pi triggered an LED via its GPIO.</p>\n<iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/54831393" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>',fields:{slug:"/projects/bathroom-vacancy-light/"},frontmatter:{title:"Bathroom Vacancy Light",created:"2012",path:null,description:"An internet of things project with Raspberry Pi and Arduino."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/voteforjordan/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>Jordan was a Florida resident who chose to let the world of Twitter decide which candidate would get his vote in the 2012 presidential election. Participants submitted their votes by hashtagging their tweets with either <a href="http://twitter.com/search?q=%23jordanvoteromney&#x26;src=typd&#x26;mode=realtime">#jordanvoteromney</a> or <a href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23jordanvoteobama&#x26;src=typd&#x26;mode=realtime">#jordanvoteobama</a>. The candidate that received the most votes was chosen on Jordanâ€™s absentee ballot.</p>\n<iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/50576416" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>\n<p>I worked on this project with a team of art directors and copywriters and led the development of the voting system as well as the website myself. I set up a continuously running PHP script that utilized the Twitter Streaming API to filter the hashtag "tweet-votes" and update the percentages on the Vote For Jordan site in real-time.</p>\n<h3>Press</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://adland.tv/adnews/vote-jordan-rich-and-end-democracy/1349403895">http://adland.tv/adnews/vote-jordan-rich-and-end-democracy/1349403895</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://www.adweek.com/agencyspy/florida-art-director-cant-decide-who-to-vote-for-solicits-twitter-help/40603">http://www.adweek.com/agencyspy/florida-art-director-cant-decide-who-to-vote-for-solicits-twitter-help/40603</a></li>\n</ul>',fields:{slug:"/projects/voteforjordan/"},frontmatter:{title:"Vote For Jordan",created:"2012",path:null,description:"A swing voter put his presidential vote up to a vote on Twitter."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/fanfare/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<iframe class="media video" width="640" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/gMG8yLw0-q0?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n<p>Fanfare allowed concertgoers to link up with Facebook friends with similar musical tastes and assisted with group ticket purchasing/distributing of funds.</p>\n<p>As a huge music fan and concertgoer myself, I came up with the idea after trying and failing to find a friend to go see <a href="http://soundcloud.com/quadronmusic">Quadron</a> with me at Rockwood Music Hall.</p>\n<p>The app was written in PHP and Javascript in less than 24 hours and utilized the Facebook and Songkick APIs for AngelHack NYC 2012. My team took home a prize from Facebook for Fanfare\'s use of the Facebook Open Graph API.</p>',fields:{slug:"/projects/fanfare/"},frontmatter:{title:"Fanfare",created:"2012",path:null,description:"A hackathon project that connected concertgoers via their music tastes."}}},{node:{id:"/Users/amaliaviti/projects/aamaliaa.github.io-new/content/projects/fourplay/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>Fourplay mashed up Craigslist Missed Connection listings and Foursquare User data to bring users missed connections that happened near or at their check-ins.</p>\n<p>In order to achieve this we:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>scraped Craigslist Missed Connections with a <a href="https://scraperwiki.com/scrapers/ottawa_craigslist_missed_connections_1/">Python script</a></li>\n<li>analyzed each post for GPS data using the (now deprecated) Metalayer Text API</li>\n<li>then used the GPS information to locate and map locations using the Factual and <a href="https://developer.foursquare.com/">Foursquare</a> APIs</li>\n</ul>\n<p>My team was awarded the Metalayer API Award for our use of their API to analyze the missed connection data.</p>\n<h3>Press</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://techcrunch.com/video/metalayer-gives-their-awards-to-sidewinder-fourplay-and-serendipity/">Metalayer Gives Their Awards to Sidewinder, Fourplay and Serendipity</a></li>\n</ul>',fields:{slug:"/projects/fourplay/"},frontmatter:{title:"Fourplay",created:"2012",path:null,description:"A hackathon mashup of Craigslist Missed Connections and Foursquare."}}}]}},pathContext:{}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---projects-9e765a11a6c945462523.js.map